                   Behold, how good and how pleasant it is   
                   for brethren to dwell together in unity!  
                                                             
                             --- The Book of Psalms          
                                                             



Early autumn, 1346: 

The great bell strikes, bolting you out of sleep. One peal---Matins, first of the eight daily offices. Two in the morning, and the wind off the Channel coast has found every gap in the Dorter walls. 

You lie in your cot still in your habit, as the monks of the priory of Our Lady of Thorns must attend office below without delay. Five months a novice here, and you have not yet made peace with the schedule.


Dorter (on your cot)

There are several of your fellow monks here---Brothers Benedict, Hugh, and Anselm---along with your mentor, Brother Aelred.

What will you do, Brother?
> REPLAY
Do you want MORE prompts? (y/n) >n
[Replaying commands.]

> * Start
[Comment recorded]

> X HIM
Your beloved mentor. Brother Aelred is in his sixties, tall and broad-shouldered, with gentle eyes that often crinkle with quiet amusement. In the five months you've studied under him, his kindness has been matched only by his knowledge of healing herbs.

Brother Hugh heads down.

> LOOK

Dorter (on your cot)
This great room is used by all the choir monks except Brother Oswald. It could easily provide rest for twenty brothers, but there are only eight cots in here now. Each cot has a chest at its foot for any meagre possessions the brother has. 

A window high up reflects pale moonlight on the floor. 

A doorway leads south to the Hall. Narrow stairs descend to the Quire, where offices are held.

You can see three Brothers (Benedict, Anselm and Aelred) here.

Brother Benedict heads down.
Brother Martin arrives from the south.

> SOUTH
(first getting up from your cot)

Hall
A plain corridor connecting the two dorters. Wooden floorboards creak underfoot. There are passages to the north, south, and east. Broad stairs lead down.

You can see Brother Wilfred here.

Brother Remigio arrives from the south.
Brother Wilfred heads north.

> DOWN

Day Stairs
You're in the middle of a set of broad stone steps. The steps dip in the centre from generations of sandaled feet. Above is the upper living areas and below is the Cloister walk.

> DOWN

Cloister Northeast
You emerge on the northern edge of the Cloister walk, the covered stone arcade at the centre of the priory. It's a continuous square path surrounding the Garth, a large open yard. Rooms and passageways come off each section of it.

Arched openings admit cold night air and pale moonlight.

The Chapter House is to the east, and the Day Stairs to the upper floor head upward from here. You can also go west to the northern end of the Cloister or south to the eastern end.

> WEST

Cloister North
Arched openings admit cold night air and pale moonlight.

The wall of the Nave rises imposingly to the north. A passageway into it leads to the Quire. You can also go west to the northwest corner, east to the northeastern corner, or south into the Garth.

> WEST

Cloister Northwest
Arched openings admit cold night air and pale moonlight.

The high walls of the church rise imposingly to the north, and a curious door lies to the west.

> EAST

Cloister North
Arched openings admit cold night air and pale moonlight.

The wall of the Nave rises imposingly to the north. A passageway into it leads to the Quire. You can also go west to the northwest corner, east to the northeastern corner, or south into the Garth.

> EAST

Cloister Northeast
Arched openings admit cold night air and pale moonlight.

The Chapter House is to the east, and the Day Stairs to the upper floor head upward from here. You can also go west to the northern end of the Cloister or south to the eastern end.

You can see an orange cat here.

Brother Oswald finds you, exasperated. "Why aren't you with the others in the Quire? This is no time to dawdle." 

He brings you down to the Quire and you find a seat.

Quire (on the stalls)
The Quire is the heart of monastic worship and the centre of the church. Two stalls face each other across a narrow gap, where the brothers gather to chant the Divine Offices. The high altar rises to the east. The Nave lies west, beyond the rood screen. The Night Stairs ascend to the Dorter, and a path leads south to the Cloister.

Brothers here:
- Aelred, the herbalist (seated)
- Anselm, the cantor (seated)
- Benedict, the infirmarer (seated)
- Cuthbert, the sacrist (seated)
- Hugh, the cellarer (seated)
- Martin, the kitchener (seated)
- Oswald, the prior (seated)
- Remigio, the lay kitchen assistant (seated)
- Wilfred, the librarian (seated)

You hear the brothers singing.

