Scriptorium
This chamber is where three of the brothers work, creating illuminated manuscripts and copying books. To the west is the Cloister; to the east is the Library. 

A fireplace has a small fire going, warming the room and helping keep the manuscripts dry from the sea air. 

A large table is at the centre where the work is done, on which are several items.

The library door is closed.

Brother Wilfred sits at the table, close to the fireplace.

> CONFESS TO WILFRED

Wilfred listens as you explain your discoveries. The coins hidden among the dead. The discovered stolen psalter. The deadly henbane decoction. The note seeking priory manuscripts. The letters to Rose, showing previous payment.

A great sadness crosses Wilfred's face. "My son," he begins, then pauses. "No. 'Aldwin'. You are no longer a child." 

He sighs deeply. "I have grown more forgiving in my old age. I no longer feel it is my place to judge others' sins---only to hear them and offer what comfort I can. 

"But you... you have chosen this life. And if you are to be a true brother here, you must be capable of making great and terrible choices." 

He looks at you steadily. "So I leave this to you, Aldwin. Will you bring these accusations to our prior? If you do, Hugh will surely hang. Or will you forgive him, even knowing justice may demand otherwise? 

"This is your choice. Choose wisely, and choose with prayer."

Do you choose justice or mercy? > MERCY

You and Brother Wilfred find Hugh and tell him to leave. Tonight. Before questions are asked. He takes flight, and you never learn what becomes of him---or Rose. 

You lied to the prior and received penance for your actions that day. At least you can give Brother Oswald the stolen psalter and sack of silver, saying you found them after being assigned to organize the Undercroft.

But when you pray before the Lady of Thorns, you remember Brother Aelred's last words: "One life for two, my son." Perhaps mercy, not justice, was what he meant. 

Still, you wonder. A murderer walks free. Does forgiveness make you holy, or complicit? You will carry this question all your days.

  *** You chose mercy ***

